1
00:01:44,880 --> 00:01:47,280
A legend is sung

2
00:01:47,280 --> 00:01:50,400
Of when England was young

3
00:01:50,400 --> 00:01:56,080
And knights
were brave and bold

4
00:01:56,080 --> 00:01:58,840
The good king had died

5
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:02,560
And no one could decide

6
00:02:02,560 --> 00:02:08,440
Who was rightful heir
to the throne

7
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,400
It seemed that the land

8
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:15,840
Would be torn by war

9
00:02:15,840 --> 00:02:17,190
Or saved by a miracle alone

10
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:28,680
And that miracle appeared

11
00:02:28,680 --> 00:02:30,360
In London town

12
00:02:36,920 --> 00:02:39,400
The sword

13
00:02:39,400 --> 00:02:40,840
In the stone

14
00:02:48,320 --> 00:02:51,400
And below the hilt
in letters of gold...

15
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:54,000
were written these words:

16
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:58,160
"Whoso pulleth out this sword
of this stone and anvil...

17
00:02:58,160 --> 00:03:02,600
is rightwise king
born of England."

18
00:03:02,600 --> 00:03:05,680
Though many tried for the sword
with all their strength...

19
00:03:05,680 --> 00:03:09,400
none could move the sword
nor stir it.

20
00:03:09,400 --> 00:03:11,920
So the miracle
had not worked.

21
00:03:11,920 --> 00:03:15,000
And England was still
without a king.

22
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:19,280
And in time, the marvellous sword
was forgotten.

23
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:26,800
This was a dark age...

24
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:30,880
without law
and without order.

25
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:34,000
Men lived in fear
of one another...

26
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,280
for the strong
preyed upon the weak.

27
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:09,840
A dark age indeed!

28
00:04:09,840 --> 00:04:12,680
Age of inconvenience.

29
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:16,400
No plumbing...

30
00:04:16,400 --> 00:04:18,720
no electricity...

31
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:20,720
no nothing!

32
00:04:22,320 --> 00:04:24,600
Oh, hang it all!

33
00:04:24,600 --> 00:04:26,640
Hang it all!

34
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:32,200
Oh, now what?
Now what?

35
00:04:32,200 --> 00:04:34,160
Leave, leave off!
Leave off!

36
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:38,160
Oh, you, you, you
fiendish chain you!

37
00:04:40,080 --> 00:04:42,120
Everything complicated.

38
00:04:42,120 --> 00:04:44,560
One big medieval mess.

39
00:04:53,600 --> 00:04:56,280
Now, uh, let me see.

40
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:59,600
He should be here in,
I'd say half an hour.

41
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:03,800
Who? Who? I'd like
to know who.

42
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:07,000
I told you, Archimedes.
I am not sure.

43
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:10,840
All I know is that someone will
be coming. Someone very important.

44
00:05:10,840 --> 00:05:12,720
Oh, pig feathers!

45
00:05:12,720 --> 00:05:15,840
Fate will direct him to me
so that I, in turn...

46
00:05:15,840 --> 00:05:18,560
may guide him to his rightful
place in the world.

47
00:05:18,560 --> 00:05:21,760
Huh! And-And you say he will
arrive in half an hour?

48
00:05:23,840 --> 00:05:27,120
Ha! Well, we'll just see.

49
00:05:27,120 --> 00:05:29,520
And you will, Archimedes.
You will.

50
00:05:29,520 --> 00:05:30,270
Ow!

51
00:05:32,720 --> 00:05:35,600
He'll be, uh, a boy.

52
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:38,480
Small boy.

53
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:41,880
Eleven, 12 years old.

54
00:05:41,880 --> 00:05:45,200
And a scrawny little fellow.

55
00:05:47,440 --> 00:05:49,760
Oh, no, no.
That can't be the one.

56
00:05:49,760 --> 00:05:53,320
Surely not. Why, that big lad
must be close onto 20.

57
00:05:53,320 --> 00:05:56,040
Ah. There he is.

58
00:05:56,040 --> 00:05:58,920
The scrawny little
fellow about 12.

59
00:05:58,920 --> 00:06:01,680
He's a regular
little grasshopper.

60
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:04,280
Look at him go.

61
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:08,160
And where-- where would you
guess he is at this very moment?

62
00:06:08,160 --> 00:06:10,760
I am not guessing,
Archimedes!

63
00:06:10,760 --> 00:06:14,560
I know where he is!

64
00:06:14,560 --> 00:06:19,200
Less than a mile from here
just beyond the forest.

65
00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:23,000
And right on schedule,
if-if all goes well.

66
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:28,200
- Quiet, Wart.
- I'm tryin' to be.

67
00:06:28,200 --> 00:06:32,440
And nobody asked you to
come along in the first place.

68
00:06:32,440 --> 00:06:36,360
- I'm not even movin'.
- Shut up.

69
00:06:36,360 --> 00:06:39,080
Aha! Here we go.

70
00:06:40,080 --> 00:06:42,280
Oh, what a set-up.

71
00:06:43,520 --> 00:06:46,120
Right smack through
the old gizzard.

72
00:06:49,800 --> 00:06:51,560
Whoa. What? Oh!

73
00:06:52,600 --> 00:06:54,920
Why, you clumsy,
little fool!

74
00:06:54,920 --> 00:06:59,680
Oh, Kay, please, I'm sorry.
I couldn't help it. Please.

75
00:06:59,680 --> 00:07:01,880
If I ever--

76
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:04,720
If I ever get my hands on,
on you, I'll, I'll ring...

77
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:07,440
your scrawny little neck,
so help me, I will.

78
00:07:07,440 --> 00:07:11,160
I'll get the arrow, Kay.
I'm sure I can find it.

79
00:07:13,960 --> 00:07:16,800
Don't tell me you're
going in there.

80
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:19,320
Why, it's swarming with wolves.

81
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:21,800
I'm not afraid.

82
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:25,440
Well, go ahead.
It's your skin, not mine.

83
00:07:25,440 --> 00:07:27,600
Go on, go on.

84
00:07:55,480 --> 00:07:57,480
There it is.
Oh, there it is.

85
00:08:24,240 --> 00:08:26,920
Whoa! What-- Oh!

86
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:32,080
Well.

87
00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:35,240
So, you, you did drop in
for tea after all.

88
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:39,320
Oh, you are a bit late,
you know.

89
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:42,960
- Oh, l, I am?
- Yes.

90
00:08:42,960 --> 00:08:45,800
Now, my name is Merlin.

91
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:49,120
Come, come,
who are you, my lad?

92
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:51,600
Oh, my name's Arthur,
but everyone calls me Wart.

93
00:08:52,280 --> 00:08:53,030
Oh.

94
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:56,240
Oh, what a perfect
stuffed owl.

95
00:08:57,520 --> 00:08:59,760
Stuff--
I, l, I beg your pardon!

96
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:02,160
He's alive and he talks.

97
00:09:02,160 --> 00:09:06,160
And certainly a great deal
better than you do.

98
00:09:06,160 --> 00:09:09,200
Oh, come, Archimedes.
Come, come now.

99
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:12,000
I, I want you
to meet the Wart.

100
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,960
Now, you must forgive him.
He's only a boy.

101
00:09:14,960 --> 00:09:19,000
Boy? Boy?
Well, I see no boy.

102
00:09:20,560 --> 00:09:23,920
- Oh, I'm sorry that l--
- That's all right.

103
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:25,960
He's much too sensitive.

104
00:09:25,960 --> 00:09:28,680
Sensitive? Huh?
Who? What? What?

105
00:09:28,680 --> 00:09:30,800
- Oh, well.
- How did you know that I was--

106
00:09:30,800 --> 00:09:33,240
Oh, th-that you would
be dropping in?

107
00:09:33,240 --> 00:09:37,720
Well, I happen to be
a wizard. A soothsayer.

108
00:09:37,720 --> 00:09:42,360
A prognosticator. I have
the power to see into the future.

109
00:09:42,360 --> 00:09:46,400
Centuries into the future!

110
00:09:46,400 --> 00:09:50,440
I, I've even been there, lad.
And I've seen all these things.

111
00:09:50,440 --> 00:09:54,640
They're, they're only plans and
small models, of course, you know.

112
00:09:54,640 --> 00:09:59,280
Now, this for instance
is a steam locomotive.

113
00:10:05,680 --> 00:10:09,200
There she goes.
Pretty good, eh?

114
00:10:13,800 --> 00:10:16,520
Now, that won't be invented
for hundreds of years!

115
00:10:16,520 --> 00:10:19,840
Oh. You mean you can see
everything before it happens?

116
00:10:19,840 --> 00:10:21,840
Yes, everything.

117
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:24,400
Uh-uh, uh-uh.
Everything, Merlin?

118
00:10:24,400 --> 00:10:28,160
Uh-- No, no,
not everything.

119
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:32,400
I, uh, I admit I didn't know
whom to expect for tea.

120
00:10:32,400 --> 00:10:34,640
But as you can see...

121
00:10:34,640 --> 00:10:38,640
I've figured the exact place.

122
00:10:38,640 --> 00:10:40,760
You're very clever, sir.

123
00:10:40,760 --> 00:10:43,560
Yes. Well, never mind
the, the, the sir.

124
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:46,800
Just, uh, plain Merlin will do.

125
00:10:46,800 --> 00:10:49,200
Now, would, would you
care for sugar?

126
00:10:49,200 --> 00:10:51,120
Oh, yes I would, please.

127
00:10:51,120 --> 00:10:54,160
All right. Sugar. Sugar?

128
00:10:58,120 --> 00:11:01,200
No, no, manners, manners, manners!
Guests first, you know that!

129
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:06,640
All right.
Say when, lad.

130
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:07,890
When!

131
00:11:09,600 --> 00:11:12,840
- Have you had any schooling?
- Oh, yes!

132
00:11:12,840 --> 00:11:18,040
I'm training to be a squire. I'm learning
the rules of combat and swordsmanship and...

133
00:11:18,040 --> 00:11:19,800
and jousting
and horsemanship.

134
00:11:19,800 --> 00:11:23,040
Oh, yes, yes, very good.
That's, that's--

135
00:11:23,040 --> 00:11:27,480
No, no, no, l--
I mean a, a, a real education.

136
00:11:27,480 --> 00:11:31,360
Mathematics. History.
Biology. Natural science.

137
00:11:31,360 --> 00:11:34,160
English. Latin. French.

138
00:11:34,160 --> 00:11:37,600
No. When! When!
Blast it all! When!

139
00:11:39,760 --> 00:11:42,240
Impudent piece of crockery.

140
00:11:45,880 --> 00:11:49,600
Boy, now, you can't--

141
00:11:53,120 --> 00:11:56,760
You can't grow up without
a decent education, you know.

142
00:11:56,760 --> 00:12:00,000
Oh, I suppose not, sir--
Merlin.

143
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:03,000
So, I am going to be
your tutor.

144
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:06,320
But I've got to get back to the castle.
They'll want me in the kitchen.

145
00:12:06,320 --> 00:12:08,800
Oh, well.
Then very well.

146
00:12:08,800 --> 00:12:12,280
We'll pack and
be on our way.

147
00:12:12,280 --> 00:12:15,040
You-- You watch now.
You'll like this.

148
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:22,920
Higitus figitus
zumba ka zing.

149
00:12:22,920 --> 00:12:26,240
I want your attention,
everything.

150
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:30,520
We're packing to leave.
Come on. Let's go.

151
00:12:30,520 --> 00:12:33,520
No, no, not you. Books are
always first, you know.

152
00:12:37,240 --> 00:12:40,920
Hockety pockety wockety whack
Abra abra dabra nack

153
00:12:40,920 --> 00:12:44,760
Shrink in size very small
We've got to save enough room for all

154
00:12:44,760 --> 00:12:48,720
Higitus figitus migitus mum
Prestidigitonium

155
00:12:56,400 --> 00:13:00,080
Alika fez, balika zez
Malaca mez meripedes

156
00:13:00,080 --> 00:13:03,560
Hockety pockety wockety--
Whoa!

157
00:13:03,560 --> 00:13:06,000
Now, stop, stop, stop, stop!

158
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:09,480
See here, sugar bowl. You're getting rough.
That poor old tea set is cracked enough.

159
00:13:10,680 --> 00:13:13,080
Now. Now, all right.
Let's start again.

160
00:13:13,080 --> 00:13:16,680
Ah, let's start-- Eh--
Oh. Where was l, boy?

161
00:13:16,680 --> 00:13:20,720
- Uh, hock-hockety pockety?
- Oh, yes, yes, that's right.

162
00:13:20,720 --> 00:13:24,040
Hockety pockety wockety wack
Odds and ends and bric-a-brac

163
00:13:24,040 --> 00:13:28,000
Be with you in just a minute,
son. Packing's almost done.

164
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:34,680
You, you, you
bungling blockhead!

165
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:37,400
Hey, easy there.
No, no, go ahead.

166
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:40,600
Dum doodly doodly doodly dum
This is the best part now.

167
00:13:40,600 --> 00:13:43,800
Higitus figitus migitus mum
Prestidigitonium

168
00:13:43,800 --> 00:13:48,360
Higitus figitus migitus mum
Prestidigitoni--

169
00:13:48,360 --> 00:13:52,400
- Ha, ha!
- What a way to pack.

170
00:13:52,400 --> 00:13:55,000
Well-- Well, now,
just a minute, boy.

171
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:59,320
How else would you get all this stuff
into one suitcase, I'd like to know?

172
00:13:59,320 --> 00:14:01,560
- Oh, but I think it's wonderful!
- Oh.

173
00:14:01,560 --> 00:14:05,720
Yes, it is rather.
Now, well...

174
00:14:05,720 --> 00:14:10,760
don't, don't you get any foolish ideas
that magic will solve all your problems.

175
00:14:10,760 --> 00:14:14,240
- Because it won't!
- But, sir, I don't have any problems.

176
00:14:14,240 --> 00:14:18,680
Oh, bah, everybody's got problems.
The world is full of problems.

177
00:14:20,640 --> 00:14:23,920
Oh, blast it all!
There, now. You see what I mean?

178
00:14:30,840 --> 00:14:33,800
See, that's the trouble
with the world today.

179
00:14:33,800 --> 00:14:39,080
Everybody butting their heads against a
brick wall. All muscle and no mentality.

180
00:14:39,080 --> 00:14:41,640
Do you want to be
all muscle and no brain?

181
00:14:41,640 --> 00:14:45,400
- I don't have any muscle.
- You don't? Well, how do you move about?

182
00:14:45,400 --> 00:14:47,600
Oh, I suppose l,
I do have a little.

183
00:14:47,600 --> 00:14:50,840
Aha. There, you see. Well, that's
enough. Now, develop your brain.

184
00:14:50,840 --> 00:14:54,680
Knowledge, wisdom. There's
the real power. Higher learning.

185
00:14:54,680 --> 00:14:56,600
That's the thing.

186
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:01,800
So, first thing tomorrow morning,
we'll start a full schedule.

187
00:15:01,800 --> 00:15:06,920
Eight hours a day. We'll have six hours
for schoolroom and two for study period.

188
00:15:06,920 --> 00:15:12,080
But l-- I don't have the time.
I have page duties.

189
00:15:12,080 --> 00:15:14,200
Uh, page duties? Ha!

190
00:15:18,480 --> 00:15:21,960
Ah, well, we'll change all that.
There's got to be a shake-up.

191
00:15:21,960 --> 00:15:25,240
Well, yes, sir.
I, I suppose so.

192
00:15:25,240 --> 00:15:29,080
How do you ever expect to amount to anything
without an education, I'd like to know?

193
00:15:29,080 --> 00:15:32,200
Even in these bungling,
backward, medieval times...

194
00:15:32,200 --> 00:15:35,840
you have got to know
where you're going, don't you?

195
00:15:35,840 --> 00:15:38,600
Ye-- Yes, sir.

196
00:15:38,600 --> 00:15:42,040
Yes, of course. So, you must
plan for the future, boy.

197
00:15:42,040 --> 00:15:45,920
You've got to find a direction.
And you've--

198
00:15:47,720 --> 00:15:51,040
Now, by the by, what direction
is this castle of yours?

199
00:15:51,040 --> 00:15:53,120
I think it's north.
The other way.

200
00:15:53,120 --> 00:15:53,960
Oh, oh.

201
00:15:56,880 --> 00:15:59,680
All right, then we better get a move on. Come
on, come on, lad. Pick up the pace. Pick it up.

202
00:15:59,680 --> 00:16:02,160
Pick it up.
Pick it up.

203
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:32,040
Yo-ho, the devil take it!
No, the devil take it.

204
00:16:32,040 --> 00:16:36,840
Anyone's got better sense than to go
barging off in that infernal forest alone.

205
00:16:36,840 --> 00:16:39,600
You had no business
letting him go.

206
00:16:39,600 --> 00:16:43,920
Look, Dad, I'm not
the Wart's keeper.

207
00:16:43,920 --> 00:16:46,280
Well, blast it all, I am.

208
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:50,480
After all, l, I took him in,
adopted the lad, you might say.

209
00:16:50,480 --> 00:16:53,360
Being his foster father,
well, I'm responsible.

210
00:16:55,480 --> 00:16:56,200
Whoop.

211
00:17:00,160 --> 00:17:03,840
Tiger! Talbot! Off with you.
Now, look here, Wart.

212
00:17:03,840 --> 00:17:06,200
What's the big idea of
gallivanting off in the woods...

213
00:17:06,200 --> 00:17:08,920
and worrying the living
daylights out of everybody?

214
00:17:08,920 --> 00:17:11,280
- I'm sorry, sir.
- Well, sorry's not enough.

215
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:14,760
That's four demerits.
Four hours extra kitchen duty.

216
00:17:14,760 --> 00:17:17,160
Eh, report to the cook!

217
00:17:17,160 --> 00:17:21,440
- But, sir, I'd like you to meet--
- Go on, hop it, boy, hop, hop, hop it!

218
00:17:21,440 --> 00:17:25,200
Well, yes, you've got to keep a tight
schedule to run a big place like this.

219
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:29,040
Need strict rules.
Especially for small boys.

220
00:17:29,040 --> 00:17:32,080
And I most certainly agree.

221
00:17:32,080 --> 00:17:35,880
Who are you and--
Oh. I mean, uh, you?

222
00:17:35,880 --> 00:17:40,040
Uh, my name is Merlin.
Uh, this is Archimedes.

223
00:17:40,040 --> 00:17:43,040
A highly educated owl.

224
00:17:43,040 --> 00:17:47,320
Educated owl?
Say, that's a good one.

225
00:17:48,640 --> 00:17:51,120
Say. Hey, I know.

226
00:17:51,120 --> 00:17:55,480
You've got him under a spell,
Marvin. You're a magician.

227
00:17:55,480 --> 00:17:59,040
The name is Merlin.

228
00:17:59,040 --> 00:18:03,800
And I happen to be the world's
most powerful wizard.

229
00:18:05,320 --> 00:18:08,560
Come off it, man.
Gadzooks!

230
00:18:08,560 --> 00:18:11,480
All right.
I shall demonstrate.

231
00:18:11,480 --> 00:18:14,320
Higitus figitus migitus moe...

232
00:18:14,320 --> 00:18:17,200
wind and snow
swirl and blow!

233
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:22,320
What the devil
are you up to?

234
00:18:22,320 --> 00:18:26,400
And that is what I call
a "wizard blizzard."

235
00:18:27,800 --> 00:18:29,960
Hey, Kay, would
you look at this?

236
00:18:29,960 --> 00:18:33,560
An indoor blizzard.
And in the month of July.

237
00:18:33,560 --> 00:18:34,520
So what?

238
00:18:36,560 --> 00:18:40,560
All right, Marvin. Turn her off.
I'm convinced.

239
00:18:41,480 --> 00:18:43,920
Alakazam!

240
00:18:45,480 --> 00:18:50,200
I, uh-- I hope you don't go in
for any of that black magic.

241
00:18:50,200 --> 00:18:52,120
Oh, no, no, no, no.

242
00:18:52,120 --> 00:18:54,280
Never touch the stuff. No.

243
00:18:54,280 --> 00:18:58,200
My magic is used mainly
for educational purposes.

244
00:19:00,960 --> 00:19:03,040
In fact, that is why
I am here.

245
00:19:03,040 --> 00:19:06,360
I have come
to educate the Wart.

246
00:19:06,360 --> 00:19:08,320
Oh, no you don't.

247
00:19:08,320 --> 00:19:11,960
I'm running this place. And if you think
you're gonna fiddle with my schedule...

248
00:19:11,960 --> 00:19:15,800
you'd better pack up your bag
of tricks and be gone.

249
00:19:15,800 --> 00:19:18,720
Wha-- Well, by Jove.

250
00:19:18,720 --> 00:19:20,600
Hey, he's gone.

251
00:19:20,600 --> 00:19:22,840
Hm-mmm. Good riddance.

252
00:19:22,840 --> 00:19:27,040
I'm gone, but then,
I'm not gone.

253
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:30,040
So, if I do leave...

254
00:19:30,040 --> 00:19:33,760
you could never be sure
that I am gone, can you?

255
00:19:33,760 --> 00:19:35,680
Well, uh--

256
00:19:37,160 --> 00:19:40,400
Well, I must say, you--
you got me there, Marvin.

257
00:19:41,840 --> 00:19:45,920
Yes. Well, you win. You're
welcome to stay if you like.

258
00:19:45,920 --> 00:19:48,560
Thank you.
You're very kind.

259
00:19:48,560 --> 00:19:51,440
Very generous, I must say.

260
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:55,480
Well, uh, all we can offer
is room and board.

261
00:19:55,480 --> 00:19:57,880
Hard times,
you know, Marvin.

262
00:19:57,880 --> 00:20:00,440
We'll put you up
in the northwest tower.

263
00:20:00,440 --> 00:20:03,080
That's the guest room.
It's a bit drafty in the winter...

264
00:20:03,080 --> 00:20:06,640
but in this blazing hot weather,
it's the best room in the house.

265
00:20:06,640 --> 00:20:09,720
Oh, yes.
Very lovely indeed.

266
00:20:09,720 --> 00:20:13,440
So just make yourself
at home, Marvin.

267
00:20:13,440 --> 00:20:16,400
Marvin, Marvin,
Marvin, Marvin.

268
00:20:31,800 --> 00:20:34,520
Best room in the house!

269
00:20:34,520 --> 00:20:38,480
Guest room!
Unwelcome-guest room!

270
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:42,760
But if he thinks that he can get rid of
me, I've got news for that old walrus.

271
00:20:42,760 --> 00:20:47,800
- I'm sticking it out.
- And I say we go back to the woods.

272
00:20:47,800 --> 00:20:50,160
No, not on your life.

273
00:20:50,160 --> 00:20:53,880
That boy's got to have an education.
He has a future.

274
00:20:53,880 --> 00:20:55,880
Well, you may be right.

275
00:20:55,880 --> 00:21:00,520
A skinny kid like that would make
a cracking good chimney sweep.

276
00:21:04,400 --> 00:21:08,760
Something tells me that
you're all wet, Archimedes.

277
00:21:17,520 --> 00:21:19,480
- Who goes there?
- Pelinore!

278
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:22,400
It's Pelinore, dash it all!

279
00:21:22,400 --> 00:21:26,560
I've got big news from London.
Big news!

280
00:21:26,560 --> 00:21:29,800
Come on, man.
Drop the bridge.

281
00:21:39,640 --> 00:21:43,200
Oh, big news, eh?

282
00:21:43,200 --> 00:21:47,720
They can't wait for the London Times. First
edition won't be out for at least, uh...

283
00:21:47,720 --> 00:21:50,000
1200 years.

284
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:53,000
Archimedes, would you mind
sailing down there and, and--

285
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:55,160
Not interested!

286
00:21:55,160 --> 00:21:58,760
Oh, come, come, come, come now.
You're as wet as you can get.

287
00:21:58,760 --> 00:22:02,040
No! No, no, no!

288
00:22:02,040 --> 00:22:05,800
Archimedes! I'll turn you
into a human.

289
00:22:05,800 --> 00:22:09,400
- Hmph! You wouldn't dare!
- I will. So help me, I will.

290
00:22:09,400 --> 00:22:12,200
Well, all right, all right.
All right!

291
00:22:12,200 --> 00:22:15,680
All right.
It works every time.

292
00:22:15,680 --> 00:22:17,760
Just like magic.

293
00:22:28,800 --> 00:22:31,680
Pelinore!

294
00:22:31,680 --> 00:22:33,920
Pelinore.

295
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:38,080
Greetings, old boy. And what's
all the noise about London, hmm?

296
00:22:38,080 --> 00:22:41,440
Big news. Really big news.

297
00:22:41,440 --> 00:22:44,200
Sit down, man,
and let's hear all about it.

298
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:47,800
They're having a big tournament
New Year's Day.

299
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:51,320
Oh, that's not news,
dash it all. They always do.

300
00:22:51,320 --> 00:22:56,480
Yeah, but, Ector-- Ector, here's
where all the excitement comes in.

301
00:22:56,480 --> 00:23:00,920
To the winner of this tournament
goes the crown.

302
00:23:03,760 --> 00:23:06,800
You mean-- You mean
he'll be King of all England?

303
00:23:07,560 --> 00:23:10,240
King of all England.

304
00:23:11,920 --> 00:23:16,240
- Kay, lad, did you hear that?
- Pretty fair prize, I'd say.

305
00:23:16,240 --> 00:23:20,040
Yes, and you can win it, boy,
if you knuckle down to your training.

306
00:23:20,040 --> 00:23:23,920
And we'll have you knighted by Christmas
and off to London. What do you say?

307
00:23:23,920 --> 00:23:26,800
Sure. Why not? Why not?

308
00:23:26,800 --> 00:23:29,880
Wart, lad, how'd you
like to go to London?

309
00:23:29,880 --> 00:23:34,160
- Oh, Sir Ector, you mean it?
- If you stick to your duties, you can be Kay's squire.

310
00:23:34,160 --> 00:23:37,360
Oh, I will, sir.
I will.

311
00:23:39,760 --> 00:23:43,040
I don't want the Wart
for my squire.

312
00:23:43,040 --> 00:23:46,240
Here's to London!
And to here's to Kay.

313
00:23:46,240 --> 00:23:50,480
And here's to the banner
of the Castle of the Forest Suavage.

314
00:23:50,480 --> 00:23:52,840
- Cheers!
- Cheers, cheers. - Cheers.

315
00:24:09,120 --> 00:24:09,960
Charge!

316
00:24:11,640 --> 00:24:14,360
Weight forward!
Lean into him!

317
00:24:14,360 --> 00:24:16,320
Steady, boy. Steady!

318
00:24:16,320 --> 00:24:19,400
Steady with the lance!
Grip her tight!

319
00:24:19,400 --> 00:24:21,600
Hit him clean!

320
00:24:21,600 --> 00:24:23,520
No, no, no!

321
00:24:27,800 --> 00:24:29,960
Heads up!

322
00:24:33,880 --> 00:24:37,840
Ar-Ar-Archimedes. Archimedes,
wh-where, where, where are we?

323
00:24:37,840 --> 00:24:40,000
In a tumble-down old tower...

324
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:44,240
in the most miserable old castle
in all Christendom, that's where.

325
00:24:44,240 --> 00:24:46,880
C-Castle? Castle?

326
00:24:46,880 --> 00:24:49,040
Don't you even
remember the boy?

327
00:24:49,040 --> 00:24:50,880
Uh, the boy?

328
00:24:50,880 --> 00:24:53,760
Can't you remember
one blasted thing?

329
00:24:53,760 --> 00:24:56,840
- Oh, now, just a moment. I--
- Tight grip on the lance.

330
00:24:56,840 --> 00:25:00,880
- Oh.
- Loosen the saddle, knees in tight.

331
00:25:00,880 --> 00:25:03,760
Weight forward
and stay on target.

332
00:25:05,760 --> 00:25:08,400
You keep losing your grip.

333
00:25:08,400 --> 00:25:11,280
It's not a mere matter
of muscle, sir.

334
00:25:11,280 --> 00:25:14,320
Jousting is, uh, uh,
a fine skill.

335
00:25:14,320 --> 00:25:17,360
It-- It's a highly
developed science.

336
00:25:18,760 --> 00:25:20,280
Science, indeed.

337
00:25:20,280 --> 00:25:24,240
One dummy trying to knock off
another dummy with a bit of a stick.

338
00:25:24,240 --> 00:25:27,440
And the Wart's just as hot
for it as the rest of them.

339
00:25:27,440 --> 00:25:32,080
He certainly is. That boy's
got real spark. Lots of spirit.

340
00:25:32,080 --> 00:25:35,560
Throws himself heart and soul
into everything he does.

341
00:25:35,560 --> 00:25:39,600
That's really worth something if it can
only be turned in the right direction.

342
00:25:39,600 --> 00:25:41,840
Ha-ha.
Fat chance of that.

343
00:25:41,840 --> 00:25:45,880
Oh, I plan to cheat,
of course.

344
00:25:45,880 --> 00:25:50,880
Use magic. Every last trick
in the trade if I have to.

345
00:26:00,840 --> 00:26:04,240
I'd give anything to go riding
about on a great white charger...

346
00:26:04,240 --> 00:26:08,600
slaying dragons and griffins
and man-eating giants.

347
00:26:08,600 --> 00:26:10,720
Well, won't you?

348
00:26:10,720 --> 00:26:13,080
Oh. No. You see.

349
00:26:13,080 --> 00:26:16,320
I'm an orphan, and a knight
must be of proper birth.

350
00:26:16,320 --> 00:26:19,240
I only hope I'm worthy
to be Kay's squire.

351
00:26:19,240 --> 00:26:21,560
That's a big job too,
you know.

352
00:26:21,560 --> 00:26:27,280
Oh, indeed, yes, yes.
I would say almost impossible. Yes.

353
00:26:27,280 --> 00:26:30,840
Well, now then. When I said
that I could swim like a fish...

354
00:26:30,840 --> 00:26:33,280
I really meant as a fish.

355
00:26:33,280 --> 00:26:36,720
You mean you can turn
yourself into a fish?

356
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:39,760
After all, I happen
to be a wizard.

357
00:26:39,760 --> 00:26:43,120
- Could you turn me into a fish?
- Well, do you have any imagination?

358
00:26:43,120 --> 00:26:45,520
Can you imagine yourself
as a fish?

359
00:26:45,520 --> 00:26:48,720
Oh, that's easy.
I've done that lots of times.

360
00:26:48,720 --> 00:26:52,560
Oh. Well, good. Then I think
that my magic can do the rest.

361
00:26:57,120 --> 00:26:59,680
Archimedes, what, what
is that fish formula?

362
00:27:03,640 --> 00:27:06,680
- Who? Who? What? What? What?
- You know, that, that, that Latin business.

363
00:27:06,680 --> 00:27:09,200
Hmm? Fish? Latin?

364
00:27:09,200 --> 00:27:11,240
Oh, uh.

365
00:27:11,240 --> 00:27:15,360
Aquarius aquaticus aqualitus.

366
00:27:15,360 --> 00:27:17,440
And-And now if you don't mind...

367
00:27:17,440 --> 00:27:21,680
I say good day to the both
of you if you please.

368
00:27:21,680 --> 00:27:23,720
When he stays out all night...

369
00:27:23,720 --> 00:27:26,800
he's always grumpy
the next morning.

370
00:27:26,800 --> 00:27:29,920
- Then he must stay out every night.
- Yes.

371
00:27:29,920 --> 00:27:34,520
Oh. Oh, yes. Oh, I say,
that's very good, boy. Very.

372
00:27:34,520 --> 00:27:36,880
Who? What? What?

373
00:27:36,880 --> 00:27:39,520
All right, boy. All set.
Here we go.

374
00:27:39,520 --> 00:27:42,480
Aquarius aquaticus
aqualitus quum.

375
00:27:42,480 --> 00:27:44,640
Aqua digi tarium.

376
00:27:48,920 --> 00:27:51,200
Merlin, am I a fish?
Am I a fish?

377
00:27:51,200 --> 00:27:53,720
Yes. Yes, yes, yes, yes,
you are a fish...

378
00:27:53,720 --> 00:27:56,440
but if you don't stop that
flippity-flopping around...

379
00:27:56,440 --> 00:27:59,320
and get in the water,
you won't last long.

380
00:28:01,960 --> 00:28:06,800
Now, now, stay right here in the tules
and I'll-- I'll be with you in a minute.

381
00:28:20,720 --> 00:28:21,470
Oh.

382
00:28:22,720 --> 00:28:26,800
So you thought you could take
right off like a shot, did you?

383
00:28:30,440 --> 00:28:33,280
Well, I am a fish,
aren't l?

384
00:28:33,280 --> 00:28:35,520
You merely look
like a fish.

385
00:28:35,520 --> 00:28:40,000
That doesn't mean that you can swim like
one. You, you don't have the instinct.

386
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:44,160
So, you'll have to use your,
your brain for a change.

387
00:28:44,160 --> 00:28:46,880
You are living between
two planes now.

388
00:28:46,880 --> 00:28:51,600
Somewhere between the ceiling
and the floor.

389
00:28:53,200 --> 00:28:55,440
Now, there, there's lots
of ups and downs...

390
00:28:55,440 --> 00:28:57,600
Like-like, uh,
like a helicopter.

391
00:28:58,720 --> 00:29:01,160
- Helicopter?
- Yes--

392
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:04,000
Oh. No, never mind.

393
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:08,160
Every flick of a fin
creates movement.

394
00:29:08,160 --> 00:29:10,400
So, first we'll start
with a caudal fin.

395
00:29:13,280 --> 00:29:15,840
No, no, boy.
Your tail. Tail.

396
00:29:20,160 --> 00:29:22,720
Now, now, that gives you
the forward thrust now.

397
00:29:22,720 --> 00:29:25,760
Come on, let's get a rhythm.
Right, left.

398
00:29:25,760 --> 00:29:29,360
Right, left. One, two.

399
00:29:29,360 --> 00:29:33,000
Left and right
Like day and night

400
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:36,320
That's what makes
the world go 'round

401
00:29:36,320 --> 00:29:40,040
In and out
Thin and stout

402
00:29:40,040 --> 00:29:43,880
That's what makes
the world go 'round

403
00:29:43,880 --> 00:29:46,880
For every up
there is a down

404
00:29:46,880 --> 00:29:49,120
- For every square
- There is a round?

405
00:29:49,120 --> 00:29:52,040
Yes.
For every high

406
00:29:52,040 --> 00:29:53,840
- There is a low?
- Uh-huh.

407
00:29:53,840 --> 00:29:56,920
- And for every to
-- - There is a-- - Fro. - Fro.

408
00:29:56,920 --> 00:30:00,960
Yes, fro.
To and fro, Stop and go

409
00:30:00,960 --> 00:30:04,640
That's what makes
the world go 'round

410
00:30:04,640 --> 00:30:07,640
In and out
Thin and stout

411
00:30:07,640 --> 00:30:09,280
- Merlin! Merlin!
- Oh!

412
00:30:09,280 --> 00:30:13,120
- I swallowed a bug!
- Oh. What's wrong with that?

413
00:30:13,120 --> 00:30:17,240
After all, ah, boy, you are
a fish. I-instinct, you know.

414
00:30:17,240 --> 00:30:20,320
- But you said I had no instinct.
- Yes, of--

415
00:30:20,320 --> 00:30:23,480
Oh. Oh, I did. Well, th-that's
neither here nor there.

416
00:30:23,480 --> 00:30:26,360
But the main thing
is you must--

417
00:30:26,360 --> 00:30:29,320
Set your sights
upon the heights

418
00:30:29,320 --> 00:30:31,840
Don't be a mediocrity

419
00:30:31,840 --> 00:30:33,840
- Mediocrity?
- That's right.

420
00:30:33,840 --> 00:30:36,880
Don't just wait
and trust to fate

421
00:30:36,880 --> 00:30:39,920
And say that's how
it's meant to be

422
00:30:39,920 --> 00:30:43,080
It's up to you
how far you go

423
00:30:43,080 --> 00:30:46,000
If you don't try
you'll never know

424
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:49,040
And so, my lad
as I've explained

425
00:30:49,040 --> 00:30:52,200
Nothing ventured
nothing gained

426
00:31:04,920 --> 00:31:08,600
Let's, let's swim through that
tall grass again. It tickles.

427
00:31:18,560 --> 00:31:21,600
Oh. Oh,
I beg your pardon.

428
00:31:21,600 --> 00:31:25,360
Me too.
For every to there is a fro

429
00:31:25,360 --> 00:31:27,800
For every stop
there is a go

430
00:31:27,800 --> 00:31:31,560
And that's what makes
the world go 'round

431
00:31:31,560 --> 00:31:35,480
Oh, let go,
let go, let go!

432
00:31:35,480 --> 00:31:38,040
Oh, you big,
bug-eyed bully, you!

433
00:31:38,040 --> 00:31:39,960
Who, me?

434
00:31:39,960 --> 00:31:42,160
Oh, here, here, here,
here, here, now, boy.

435
00:31:42,160 --> 00:31:46,440
There's no sense in going
around insulting bullfrogs.

436
00:31:46,440 --> 00:31:49,600
A fish has plenty of other
problems without that.

437
00:31:49,600 --> 00:31:52,520
The water world has its
forests and its jungles too.

438
00:31:52,520 --> 00:31:57,080
So it has its tigers and
its wolves. And that, eh, ah--

439
00:31:57,080 --> 00:31:59,880
That's what makes
the world go 'round

440
00:31:59,880 --> 00:32:02,480
You see, my boy
it's nature's way

441
00:32:02,480 --> 00:32:04,880
Upon the weak
the strong ones prey

442
00:32:04,880 --> 00:32:07,800
The human life
it's also true

443
00:32:07,800 --> 00:32:10,800
The strong will try
to conquer you

444
00:32:10,800 --> 00:32:13,360
And that is what
you must expect

445
00:32:13,360 --> 00:32:16,080
Unless you use
your intellect

446
00:32:16,080 --> 00:32:18,160
Brains and brawn
Weak and strong

447
00:32:18,160 --> 00:32:21,920
- Help, Merlin! Help! Help!
- That's what makes the wor--

448
00:32:21,920 --> 00:32:24,280
Jehoshaphat!

449
00:32:24,280 --> 00:32:25,030
Oh!

450
00:32:31,640 --> 00:32:33,640
- Quick, Merlin, the magic!
- No, no.

451
00:32:33,640 --> 00:32:37,240
You're on your own, lad.
Now's your chance to prove my point.

452
00:32:37,240 --> 00:32:39,320
Wha-What point?

453
00:32:39,320 --> 00:32:42,840
He's the brawn and you're the brain.
Oh, now, don't, don't, don't panic!

454
00:32:42,840 --> 00:32:46,040
You use your head.
Outsmart the big brute.

455
00:32:49,080 --> 00:32:52,520
Smart move, lad!
That's using the old intellect.

456
00:33:34,920 --> 00:33:38,560
- Bravo, boy! Great strategy!
- Is the lesson about over?

457
00:33:38,560 --> 00:33:40,800
D-D-Did you get the point?

458
00:33:40,800 --> 00:33:43,080
Yes, yes, brain over brawn.

459
00:33:43,080 --> 00:33:45,480
Okay, lad, I'll fix the big
brute. Higgeldy piggeldy--

460
00:33:45,480 --> 00:33:49,000
No, no. Hocus pocus--
Now, what in blaze-- Eh--

461
00:33:50,680 --> 00:33:52,920
Merlin!

462
00:33:54,360 --> 00:33:58,200
Now what? Oh, it's,
it's that, that boy!

463
00:33:58,200 --> 00:34:02,960
- Wh-Wh-What in b-blazes!
- Help! Help! Help!

464
00:34:04,320 --> 00:34:05,570
Ouch!

465
00:34:13,520 --> 00:34:14,770
Help!

466
00:34:19,680 --> 00:34:21,520
Archimedes!

467
00:34:21,520 --> 00:34:23,480
Help!

468
00:34:50,440 --> 00:34:53,360
What in thunder is a monster
like that doing in the moat?

469
00:34:53,360 --> 00:34:57,640
By George, l-l-l-- I'll, I'll--
I'll turn him into a minnow.

470
00:34:57,640 --> 00:35:01,120
- Merlin!
- Oh! Oh, there you are, boy.

471
00:35:01,120 --> 00:35:03,560
Snick snack snorum!

472
00:35:03,560 --> 00:35:07,120
How in the world did you ever
get out of that mess?

473
00:35:07,120 --> 00:35:12,160
That, that big fish almost swallowed me
and, and Archimedes, he, he saved me.

474
00:35:12,160 --> 00:35:15,840
Well, by George.
